SIMPLE: dissolve
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Dissolve
<hw>Dis*solve"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Dissolved</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Dissolving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>dissolvere</ets>, <ets>dissolutum</ets>; <ets>dis-</ets> +
<ets>solvere</ets> to loose, free. See <er>Solve</er>, and cf.
<er>Dissolute</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To separate into competent
parts; to disorganize; to break up; hence, to bring to an end by
separating the parts, sundering a relation, etc.; to terminate; to
destroy; to deprive of force; <as>as, to <ex>dissolve</ex> a
partnership; to <ex>dissolve</ex> Parliament.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lest his ungoverned rage <qex>dissolve</qex> the life.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To break the continuity of; to disconnect; to
disunite; to sunder; to loosen; to undo; to separate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nothing can <qex>dissolve</qex> us.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Down fell the duke, his joints <qex>dissolved</qex> asunder.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For one people to <qex>dissolve</qex> the political bands which
have connected them with another.</q> <rj><qau>The Declaration of
Independence.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To convert into a liquid by means of heat, moisture,
etc.,; to melt; to liquefy; to soften.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As if the world were all <qex>dissolved</qex> to tears.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To solve; to clear up; to resolve.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Dissolved</xex> the mystery.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Make interpretations and <qex>dissolve</qex> doubts.</q>
<rj><qau>Dan. v. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To relax by pleasure; to make powerless.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Angels <qex>dissolved</qex> in hallelujahs lie.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>To annul; to rescind; to discharge
or release; <as>as, to <ex>dissolve</ex> an injunction</as>.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Adjourn</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dissolve</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Dissolve
<hw>Dis*solve"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To waste away; to
be dissipated; to be decomposed or broken up.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To become fluid; to be melted; to be
liquefied.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A figure⟦br⟧
Trenched in ice, which with an hour's heat⟦br⟧
<qex>Dissolves</qex> to water, and doth lose his form.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To fade away; to fall to nothing; to lose
power.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The charm <qex>dissolves</qex> apace.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>dissolved</ent>⟦br⟧
